			"title": "房地产",
			"body": "<p>A lack of investment options means that China’s burgeoning middle class has historically put its wealth in housing. Local governments and state-owned enterprises rely on land prices as a major asset and source of income.</p>\n<p>Many commentators expect that the housing sector’s contribution to economic growth will continue to shrink. Some point to localised property bubbles, such as in Shenzhen and Hong Kong, which have an average price-to-income ratio of 18 and 16 respectively, compared with London’s 10. This year China starts a new five-year-plan that prioritises supply-side reforms, such as reducing the stock of unsold housing.</p>",
